\section{\textsc{confession of sin}}

\bcpinst{The Officiant says to the People}

Let us humbly confess our sins unto Almighty God.

\bcpinst{Silence is kept. All kneeling, the Officiant and People say}

\begin{poem}
\begin{stanza}
\textbf{
Almighty and most merciful Father, \verseline
\verseindent we have erred and strayed from thy ways like lost sheep. \verseline
We have followed too much the devices and desires \verseline
\verseindent of our own hearts. \verseline
We have offended against thy holy laws. \verseline
We have left undone those things which we ought to have done, \verseline
\verseindent and we have done those things which we ought not \verseline
\verseindent to have done; \verseline
\verseindent and apart from thy grace, there is no health in us. \verseline
But thou, O Lord, have mercy upon us, miserable offenders. \verseline
Spare thou those, O God, who confess their faults. \verseline
Restore thou those who are penitent, according to thy promises \verseline
\verseindent declared unto mankind in Christ Jesus our Lord. \verseline
And grant, O most merciful Father, for his sake, \verseline
\verseindent that we may hereafter live a godly, righteous, and sober life, \verseline
\verseindent to the glory of thy holy Name. Amen.
}
\end{stanza}
\end{poem}

\bcpinst{A Deacon or layperson remains kneeling and prays}

Grant, we beseech thee, merciful Lord, to thy faithful people pardon and peace, that we may be cleansed from all our sins, and serve thee with a quiet mind; through Jesus Christ our Lord. \textbf{Amen.}

